<h2>Part 1: Image Creative Design: Visual Hammer and Attention Economics</h2>
<h3>1.1 The Golden 3-Second Rule and First Frame Design</h3>
<p>Users' average dwell time in newsfeeds is only 1.7 seconds, meaning ad images must accomplish two tasks within extremely short timeframes: <strong>attracting attention</strong> and <strong>delivering core value</strong>.</p>
<p><strong>Five-Element Model for High-Conversion First Frame Design:</strong></p>
<ul>
<li><strong>Contrast Priority</strong>: Using colors significantly different from platform backgrounds increases CTR by an average of 23%</li>
<li><strong>Face Attraction Principle</strong>: Ad images containing human faces see a 38% increase in attention (EyeTrack research data)</li>
<li><strong>Text Anchor</strong>: Place concise text featuring core selling points in the upper-left or center area</li>
<li><strong>White Space Breathing</strong>: Avoid information overload, maintain 15-20% white space around core elements</li>
<li><strong>Brand Logo Weakening</strong>: Overexposing brand logos reduces click intent; logos should not exceed 5% of the area</li>
</ul>
<h3>1.2 Industry-Specific Design Strategies</h3>
<p><strong>Fashion &amp; Apparel:</strong></p>
<p>Creative for this category centers on <strong>scenario-based presentation</strong> and <strong>emotional resonance</strong>. Recommended design framework:</p>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Model Outfit Scene Image</strong> + <strong>Product Detail Close-up</strong> + <strong>Price Promotion Info</strong> = High-Conversion Combination</p>
</blockquote>
<p>Testing data from a fast-fashion DTC site shows that ads using the "scene image + detail image + price tag" three-panel layout achieved a CTR of 4.2%, a 156% increase compared to single-image design. Specific layout recommendation: Left 60% displays model outfit scene, right 40% vertically arranges product detail images and pricing information.</p>
