<h3>3.3 Common Copywriting Mistakes to Avoid</h3>
<blockquote>
<p><strong>Warning List: These copywriting approaches will significantly reduce ad performance</strong></p>
</blockquote>
<ol>
<li><strong>Feature-Stacking Type</strong>: Listing all product features, lacking core highlights, users cannot understand value within 3 seconds</li>
<li><strong>Empty Promise Type</strong>: Using superlatives like "best" and "top-tier" without specific data support</li>
<li><strong>Dual-Edge CTA Type</strong>: Requiring three actions simultaneously - "Follow + Buy + Download" - conversion path too long</li>
<li><strong>Grammar Error Type</strong>: Especially for multi-language delivery, machine translation can cause serious semantic deviations</li>
<li><strong>Promotion Fatigue Type</strong>: Long-term high-frequency use of "discount" and "lowest price" damages brand premium</li>
</ol>
<h2>Part 4: Creative Testing Methodology: Systematic A/B Testing Practice</h2>
<h3>4.1 Test Matrix Design Principles</h3>
<p>Scientific creative testing requires controlling variables. Common testing dimensions include:</p>
<p><strong>Primary Variables (Only change 1 per test):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Visual style (A/B test different images/videos)</li>
<li>Copy core selling points (test different value propositions)</li>
<li>CTA button copy ("Shop Now" vs "Free Trial")</li>
<li>Audience targeting (different interest tags or demographic attributes)</li>
</ul>
<p><strong>Secondary Variables (Can combine test):</strong></p>
<ul>
<li>Color style (warm vs cool tones)</li>
<li>Visual composition (person-centered vs product close-up)</li>
<li>Price presentation method (discount percentage vs specific amount)</li>
</ul>
